Footnotes<br>
<br>
1a. Tal Hraptur - from the ancient Jarsathi tongue, loosely translates to &quot;those who tear apart&quot;. This refers to the fact that the original Jarsathi monk-warriors literally tore apart their enemies during and after combat. Not only did they mutilate the bodies of dead enemies, but ancient Jarsathi had a nasty habit of also eating their fallen victims. Emperor Venril found the practice a bit unsettling and abolished cannibalism soon after assimilating the other four tribes. <br>
<br>
1b. Tak Harastur - the Kunzar dialect had butchered the original spelling and meaning of the Tal Hraptur. In the Kunzar tongue, the same words grossly translate to &quot;those who are pretty damn scary&quot;. This is how the group came to be known as the Brood of Fear. <br>
<br>
2. Jarsath - one of the five original Iksar tribe-states before Vekin's Sebilis Empire. The tribes were Kunzar, Kylong, Nathsar, Jarsath, and Obulus. <br>
<br>
3. Cazic Thule - the Iksar people worship this faceless deity, who rules over the Plane of Fear. <br>
<br>
4. Sputnik Fizzalotopus - a very smart Gnome, of supra-genius intellect, professor emeritus at the University of Ak'Anon. Also the author of this documentary. <br>
